49:16.520 --> 49:27.665 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Finally tonight,
a "NewsHour"
essay.

49:27.698 --> 49:32.636 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
As we reported earlier,
President Obama today
announced plans to expand drug
treatment centers

49:32.670 --> 49:38.509 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and increase the use of drugs
that reverse
the effect of opioids like
heroin, OxyContin

49:38.542 --> 49:40.377 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and Percocet.

49:40.411 --> 49:44.448 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Communities across the country
are developing
new approaches to this epidemic
in an attempt

49:44.481 --> 49:49.053 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to support addicts, helping them
into treatment,
instead of arrests.

49:49.086 --> 49:55.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
New York's Cardozo Law School
Professor Ekow
Yankah compares today's approach
to heroin

49:55.159 --> 50:00.130 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
users to the tough-on-crime
response a few
decades ago to those using crack
cocaine.

50:00.164 --> 50:04.268 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EKOW YANKAH, Professor, Cardozo
School of
Law: That Kroger, the Midwestern
grocery chain,

50:04.301 --> 50:08.906 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has decided to make the heroin
overdose drug
naloxone available without a
prescription

50:08.939 --> 50:11.909 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is a sign of how ominous the
current epidemic
has grown.

50:11.942 --> 50:17.481 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Faced with a rising wave of
addiction, misery,
crime and death, our nation has
linked arms

50:17.515 --> 50:23.721 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to save souls. Senators and
CEOs, Midwestern
pharmacies and even
tough-on-crime Republican

50:23.754 --> 50:29.026 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
presidential candidates now
speak with moving
compassion about the real people
crippled

50:29.059 --> 50:30.928 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
by addiction.

50:30.961 --> 50:35.332 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It wasn't always this way.
Thirty years ago,
America was facing a similar
wave of addiction,

50:35.366 --> 50:39.737 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
death and crime, and the
response could not
have been more different.
Television brought

50:39.770 --> 50:45.876 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
us endless images of thin,
black, ravaged
bodies, always with desperate,
dried lips.

50:45.910 --> 50:48.512 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We learned the words crack baby.

50:48.545 --> 50:53.117 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Back then, when addiction was a
black problem,
there was no wave of national
compassion.

50:53.150 --> 50:59.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Instead, we were warned of super
predators,
young, faceless black men
wearing bandannas

50:59.723 --> 51:01.425 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and sagging jeans.

51:01.458 --> 51:06.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
No matter how far from our lives
crack was,
we're guilty by association. By
the time I

51:06.430 --> 51:11.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was in college in the early
1990s, my short
dreadlocks meant older women
would cross the

51:11.268 --> 51:13.070 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
street to avoid me.

51:13.103 --> 51:18.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
African-Americans were cast as
pathological.
Their plight was evidence of
collective moral

51:18.175 --> 51:24.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
failure, of welfare mothers and
rock-slinging
thugs and a reason to cut off
all help. Blacks

51:24.315 --> 51:28.852 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
would just have to pull
themselves out of
the crack epidemic. Until then,
the only answer

51:28.886 --> 51:32.623 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
lay in cordoning off the
wreckage with militarized
policing.

51:32.656 --> 51:37.628 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Today, police chiefs facing
heroin addiction
are responding not by invoking
war, but by

51:37.661 --> 51:42.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
trying to save lives and get
people into rehab.
Suddenly, crime is understood as
a sign of

51:42.833 --> 51:46.937 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
underlying addiction, rather
than a scourge
to be eradicated.

51:46.971 --> 51:51.041 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One former narcotics officers
said: "These
are people. They have a purpose
in life, and

51:51.075 --> 51:53.010 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we can't look at it any other
way."

51:53.043 --> 51:58.349 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But he couldn't quite put his
finger on just
what had changed. His words
reflect our collective

51:58.382 --> 52:04.421 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
self-denial. It is hard to
describe how bittersweet
many African-Americans feel
witnessing this.

52:04.455 --> 52:10.461 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Glad to be rid of a failed war
on drugs? Yes,
but also weary and embittered.
When the faces

52:10.494 --> 52:15.032 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of addiction had dark skin, the
police didn't
see sons and daughters, sister
and brothers.

52:15.065 --> 52:21.171 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They saw brothas, young thugs to
be locked
up, not people with a purpose in
life.

52:21.205 --> 52:26.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
No one laments the violence the
crack bomb
set off more than
African-Americans. But how

52:26.477 --> 52:32.750 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
we respond to the crimes
accompanying addiction
depends on how much we care
about those affected.

52:32.783 --> 52:37.921 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
White heroin addicts get
overdose treatment,
rehabilitation and
reincorporation. Black

52:37.955 --> 52:42.192 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
drug users got jail cells and
just say no.

52:42.226 --> 52:47.197 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It would be perverse to want to
go back, and
this is not just about racial
guilt. The hope

52:47.231 --> 52:52.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is that we really can learn from
our meanest
moments. This stark moment gives
us the opportunity

52:52.202 --> 52:55.406 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to quit our dedication to
ignoring racism.

52:55.439 --> 53:00.310 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Next time we or even you are
faced with an
indictment of institutionalized
racism, maybe

53:00.344 --> 53:04.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
we can swallow the knee-jerk
dismissal or
the condescending
finger-wagging, and imagine

53:05.015 --> 53:09.119 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
if you would accept such
treatment of your
own. We don't have to wait until
a problem

53:09.153 --> 53:11.989 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
